SIMPLE: rude
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rude
<hw>Rude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Ruder</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Rudest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[F., fr. L. <ets>rudis</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Characterized by roughness; umpolished; raw; lacking
delicacy or refinement; coarse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such gardening tools as art, yet <qex>rude</qex>, . . . had
formed.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> Hence, specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Unformed by taste
or skill; not nicely finished; not smoothed or polished; -- said
especially of material things; <as>as, <ex>rude</ex>
workmanship</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Rude</xex> was the cloth.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Rude</qex> and unpolished stones.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Stillingfleet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heaven-born child⟦br⟧
All meanly wrapt in the <qex>rude</qex> manger lies.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Of untaught manners; unpolished; of low rank;
uncivil; clownish; ignorant; raw; unskillful; -- said of persons, or of
conduct, skill, and the like.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Mine ancestors were
<xex>rude</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <-- impolite. --> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was but <qex>rude</qex> in the profession of arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir H. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>the <qex>rude</qex> forefathers of the hamlet sleep.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>Violent; tumultuous; boisterous; inclement; harsh;
severe; -- said of the weather, of storms, and the like; <as>as, the
<ex>rude</ex> winter</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Clouds] pushed with winds, <qex>rude</qex> in their shock.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>rude</qex> agitation [of water] breaks it into foam.</q>
<rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>Barbarous; fierce; bloody; impetuous; -- said of
war, conflict, and the like; as, the <xex>rude</xex> shock of
armies.</def> <sd>(e)</sd> <def>Not finished or complete; inelegant;
lacking chasteness or elegance; not in good taste; unsatisfactory in
mode of treatment; -- said of literature, language, style, and the
like.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>rude</xex> Irish books.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Rude</qex> am I in my speech.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unblemished by my <qex>rude</qex> translation.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Impertinent; rough; uneven; shapeless;
unfashioned; rugged; artless; unpolished; uncouth; inelegant; rustic;
coarse; vulgar; clownish; raw; unskillful; untaught; illiterate;
ignorant; uncivil; impolite; saucy; impudent; insolent; surly; currish;
churlish; brutal; uncivilized; barbarous; savage; violent; fierce;
tumultuous; turbulent; impetuous; boisterous; harsh; inclement; severe.
See <er>Impertiment</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Rude"ly</wf> <pr>(#)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Rude"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rudenture</ent>⟦br⟧
